snippet.textDisplay:
Actually, background lore throughout all of the Kirby games (including alternate timelines which show things that do exist and could have happened), combined with the final boss fight of Kirby Star Allies, heavily hints at Kirby's origins. And a huge part of the answer lies in the butterflies. Yes, you read that right, the *butterflies*.
Also, I personally believe Meta Knight is the same or a similar species as Kirby, and that Meta Knight only fights Kirby in order to train Kirby to be able to fight and wield his power better.
snippet.textOriginal:
Actually, background lore throughout all of the Kirby games (including alternate timelines which show things that do exist and *could* have happened), combined with the final boss fight of Kirby Star Allies, heavily hints at Kirby's origins. And a huge part of the answer lies in the butterflies. Yes, you read that right, the *butterflies*.
Also, I personally believe Meta Knight is the same or a similar species as Kirby, and that Meta Knight only fights Kirby in order to train Kirby to be able to fight and wield his power better.

snippet.textDisplay:
Kirby is a sentient universe, not our universe and not the game's universe, Kirby is a 'third player' in the sense that when you play a Kirby's game, there's the universe of the player, aka our universe then the game's universe the one where all the characters exist and then Kirby himself, he is an entire separate universe

Everything Kirby consumes ends floating in a infinite pocket dimension, completely frozen in time yet available for Kirby to consume again and again so he can continue to use abilities he used in the past, Kirby can access this storage of information and power by simply eating himself a way to flip himself inside out, then he just floats inside himself and once he finds the power he wanted he eats said power again, the power source reappears inside the pocket dimension but in another place, Kirby gains the copycat he wanted and then he can eat himself again to flip back into existence with the copycat power active

None of this makes sense, he is essentially creating energy from nowhere, creating perfect copies of stuff he already ate and he can pop in and out of existence at will

But this starts to make sense once we remember that universes don't necessarily have to follow the laws of physics.

Our real life universe is expanding faster than light utilizing dark energy as fuel, the problem is dark energy is created by the expansion itself, that means the bigger the universe is the more dark energy it has to expand more, this is why the expansion rate of out universe even though it already is faster than light it can keep growing faster and faster, creating energy from absolutely nothing

Kirby functions in this exact way, he eats so he can copycat knowledge and power, and he expands to create dark energy to which he uses to fuel his impossible powers and to keep stuff he already ate alive and frozen in time, inside him

You wanted to know what Kirby is, there you go, i just hope you don't grow in fear now that you can see what cosmic horrors see when they see Kirby

snippet.textDisplay: Kirby has a very Basic sense of Morality and has been narrated to be able to talk in Kirby's Epic Yarn but is for all intents and purposes is about as emotion complex as a 6 year old. He will take action against things he perceives as wrong, like Dedede stealing all the food or stopping dreams from happening by shattering the star rod, but doesn't actually think about the great implications of those action and just stops bad people from doing back things. That second example is particularly important because Dedede by breaking the star rod was also preventing a melevolent embodiment of nightmares from escaping into the world. Obviously that's not the only way to solve that problem but Kirby doesn't even thing about solving it and merely deals with the problem as soon as it appears before him the same way he dealt with Dedede mere moments before. This is a common occurrence with him, he doesn't seem to learn yet always seems to make it through anyways.

snippet.textDisplay:
Kirby doesn't destroy the matter he consumes. It goes to a pocket universe that is contained within him. His copy ability comes from him drawing on the power of the thing he drew into that universe. I'm pretty sure this isn't just from the anime, but they definitely go over this in detail in the anime. And like you said, you believe anime.


As for his origin, the anime embellishes on what the games tell us, that Kirby and Meta Knight are either the same kind of creature or are similar kinds. And Galacta Knight, the greatest warrior in the galaxy, is basically the same kind of creature as Meta Knight, or there's at least some link there. So Kirby being so powerful makes sense if he's basically coming from the same stock as the greatest warrior in the galaxy. (In the anime they say he's literally from the same "star warrior" meta-species but he's immature, was awoken too early, and that's why he's an idiot savant – but we shouldn't believe anime too much.)


Brian, next time you do research for this series, instead of having a crisis, just DM me. I'd be happy to help.
